WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.860
And just provide, this is the last of the kind of single agent menin inhibitor data

00:00:04.860 --> 00:00:05.960
that we will go through.

00:00:06.140 --> 00:00:10.960
And again, I can skip through the background, thanks to our previous talks, and just highlight

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:13.200
again that these really are different compounds.

00:00:13.780 --> 00:00:17.920
They are all quite similar, as if domino has more of a different structure, but then you

00:00:17.920 --> 00:00:21.520
can look at, you know, the different bonds encircled with enzominib is the fact that

00:00:21.520 --> 00:00:23.040
it's an amide bond.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:29.620
And really the point of this slide is kind of talking about enzominib specifically in

00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:34.900
terms of how it was designed to hopefully have a lower lipophilicity, so that you have

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:40.100
kind of more rapidly clearing drug without the same accumulation.

00:00:41.660 --> 00:00:43.920
And highlighted here, it goes through it again.

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:49.000
So you have enzominib in green, and then you have the three other menin inhibitors that

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:50.840
are listed in purple, blue, and yellow.

00:00:51.120 --> 00:00:56.000
And you'll, so the half-life of enzominib is shorter, right?

00:00:56.020 --> 00:00:56.960
It's a BID drug.

00:00:57.060 --> 00:00:59.220
It's two to three hours without azoles.

00:00:59.240 --> 00:01:04.880
It's about three to four hours with azoles, so it's not identified to have strong SIP

00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:09.900
interaction, but yet actually that's based on an FDA definition that requires significant

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:14.580
effects, and actually the AUC does increase by about 40% when you're using enzominib with

00:01:14.580 --> 00:01:20.000
azoles, but that doesn't reach the level of a strong interaction with minimal to no

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:20.440
accumulation.

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:23.320
And so that's what kind of the figure is showing you.

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:29.220
So when you look at, for instance, menin inhibitor two in blue, you see kind of less,

00:01:29.220 --> 00:01:33.220
less accumulation, the number doesn't get quite as high, and then you have pretty rapid

00:01:33.220 --> 00:01:38.940
intracellular washout, whereas the purple and the yellow, you have kind of a very high

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:40.040
levels of accumulation.

00:01:40.040 --> 00:01:47.520
You look at the concentration and then shorter, or I'm sorry, not a less rapid washout, whereas

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:52.160
enzominib, you know, according to the sumitomo slides that I'm sharing, you know, is kind

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:58.640
of that perfect compound where you have adequate, good accumulation, and then a more rapid

00:01:58.640 --> 00:01:59.100
washout.

00:01:59.100 --> 00:01:59.180
Okay.

00:01:59.220 --> 00:02:05.340
And so this is the phase one, two study design of enzominib, and I'll take you through the

00:02:05.340 --> 00:02:07.920
monotherapy data and also the initial combination data.

00:02:08.120 --> 00:02:11.420
These are both presented at ASH this past December.

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:16.540
And so starting with the monotherapy, there were 116 patients treated.

00:02:17.220 --> 00:02:20.760
The median age was about 55, so average, a little bit younger.

00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:24.180
And then I've highlighted, you know, prior treatments are two.

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:29.100
And you'll notice that three quarters of patients had had prior venetoclax, about a third had

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:31.960
had a transplant, 10% had had a prior menin inhibitor.

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:35.880
Of course, you know, this came along after rivuminib and zipdominib had already gone

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:37.660
through the development process.

00:02:37.660 --> 00:02:42.600
And so some patients had already had a menin inhibitor, just over half were KMT2A rearranged

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:46.380
with, you know, a smattering of the various different KMT2A rearrangements.

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:52.180
When you look at AEs, right, we need to kind of be thinking about the AE profiles of these

00:02:52.180 --> 00:02:53.280
different menin inhibitors.

00:02:53.280 --> 00:02:58.980
On the left are any AEs, regardless of causality, and then on the right are what are

00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:02.120
thought, were thought by the investigator to be related to enzominib.

00:03:02.620 --> 00:03:08.000
You'll notice, you know, a decent amount of cytopenias, more of them, you know, in all

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.600
populations with, of course, relapsed leukemia.

00:03:11.540 --> 00:03:15.060
Fewer, when you get to grade three or higher, thought to be related to enzominib.

00:03:15.940 --> 00:03:19.720
When you look at differentiation syndrome and QT prolongation, which I've highlighted

00:03:19.720 --> 00:03:27.320
in yellow, you do see about a 13% DS overall, with grade three or higher being about 8%.

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:28.860
And QT prolongation.

00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:32.740
So, again, we're looking at about a 13% DS overall, with grade three or higher being about

00:03:32.740 --> 00:03:33.740
8%.

00:03:33.740 --> 00:03:35.280
And QT prolongation was described in a handful of patients, but none grade three or higher.

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:36.280
No DLTs on this study were identified.

00:03:36.280 --> 00:03:43.540
So, when you look at the response rates, you may have noticed that we're going from 116

00:03:43.540 --> 00:03:47.720
or so patients in the monotherapy down to, you know, far fewer when you're looking at

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:50.240
who is actually deemed to be response-evaluable.

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:53.960
And there's kind of a small little bullet in the bottom right saying, you know, that

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:56.960
you had to have received 200 BID or higher.

00:03:56.960 --> 00:03:58.500
You had to have not had had a prior menin inhibitor.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:01.520
And you had to have had excess blast to begin with.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:06.140
And so, you're kind of shrinking down the number of efficacy of valuable patients.

00:04:06.140 --> 00:04:12.280
In the KMT2A rearranged cohort, 300 BID was identified to be the recommended phase two

00:04:12.280 --> 00:04:13.280
dose.

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:17.320
And you're seeing a composite CR rate, CR, CRH, CRI of 60%.

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:21.660
There is a bit of a difference, more with menin inhibitors than in most other AML studies

00:04:21.660 --> 00:04:25.040
of a difference between CR, CRH and CR, CRI.

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:28.380
Meaning that there are a lot of patients that are responding, but that don't have adequate,

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:30.200
platelet count recovery.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:35.000
And so, certainly, that this was also seen in enzominib, and I think is kind of an interesting

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.880
thing about menin inhibitors.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:42.860
NPM1, they have not, as of this presentation, identified the recommended phase two dose.

00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:47.460
But what they're highlighting here is that at all the doses above 200, you're seeing,

00:04:47.460 --> 00:04:51.560
again, impressive composite remission rates.

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:56.160
Certainly when you're including all overall response rates, and then even the composite

00:04:56.160 --> 00:04:57.160
CR and CR, CRH.

00:04:57.160 --> 00:04:58.160
DR.

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:02.860
So, when you look at overall, all of these different, the NPM1 and KMT2A rearranged at

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:09.440
doses of 200 or higher, the overall CR, CRH is 44%, which as a, kind of as a number compared

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:14.880
to revuminib and zifdominib, which was about 20 to 25%, appears superior, but again, these

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:22.220
were later, this is a later study, and it's hard to compare.

00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:27.260
Overall survival is shown here for KMT2A, NPM1, I think it's, again, you know, it's

00:05:27.260 --> 00:05:27.940
in a monotherapy phase.

00:05:27.940 --> 00:05:31.960
One study, it's hard to really truly know, kind of what this OS means.

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:37.140
But in NPM1 patients, right, that are median of two prior lines of therapy, almost everyone

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:38.940
has already seen venetoclax.

00:05:38.940 --> 00:05:43.760
Gus highlighted the fact that these patients have an OS of about, you know, two to four

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:46.060
months really in multiple salvages.

00:05:46.060 --> 00:05:49.760
So it does, even though you would think maybe it would be higher, this really is, is actually

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:52.020
an impressive number.

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:56.720
And then real quick, looking at the, so this is relapsed also, but relapsed now looking

00:05:56.720 --> 00:05:57.720
at a triplet regimen.

00:05:57.720 --> 00:06:04.860
And part one was dose finding, 140, 200, 300 BID, it moved into 300 BID as the ideal combination

00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:05.860
with azaven.

00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:13.600
40 patients treated, again, median range, average age is about 59 with a range.

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:17.300
Highlighted are the fact that, again, you've got two prior lines of therapy on average.

00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:21.780
About a third of patients had had prior ven, about a, just over a quarter had had a prior

00:06:21.780 --> 00:06:24.160
menin inhibitor.

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:27.500
And they, it is highlighted here, identifying again.

00:06:27.500 --> 00:06:32.540
No DLTs, no treatment-related deaths, DS was lower.

00:06:32.540 --> 00:06:35.680
When you're putting things in combination, you don't see as much DS.

00:06:35.680 --> 00:06:37.120
Grade three or higher was zero.

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:41.260
Grade three or higher QT prolongation was zero.

00:06:41.260 --> 00:06:47.100
And then looking at clinical activity, kind of across the board, even at that lower enzomative

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:51.880
dose of 140 BID, we're seeing really impressive responses.

00:06:51.880 --> 00:06:55.820
Composite CRs and objective CRs kind of numbers are highlighted here and are impressive.

00:06:55.820 --> 00:06:57.280
And then looking now at those.

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:04.040
Those who are ven and menin inhibitor naive, seeing a composite CR rate of over 60%.

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:08.640
So these numbers, of course, look quite good in a relapsed setting where people have had

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:12.780
two prior lines of therapy.

00:07:12.780 --> 00:07:14.960
We talked a little bit about transplant.

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:16.800
About six of these patients went to transplant.

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:20.460
Two of the lines along the top are patients that went to transplant and were able to start

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:22.040
enzomative after transplant.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:27.060
So certainly it does seem that some of those patients are at the top of the list.

00:07:27.060 --> 00:07:29.740
But then again, the duration of treatment in the swimmers plot, on average, is only about

00:07:29.740 --> 00:07:30.800
four cycles or so.

00:07:30.800 --> 00:07:35.820
So certainly we need more follow-up time.

00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:41.000
Two final slides to show, just to kind of compare, as we're trying to figure out what

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:43.560
these different drugs, they are a little bit different, right?

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:45.240
You will see DS across the board.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:49.300
There is maybe a hint that there's less DS with Plexi and enzomative.

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:53.180
Or maybe it's just that we've learned menin inhibitors cause DS and we're being smarter

00:07:53.180 --> 00:07:55.820
about managing it as these studies are happening later.

00:07:55.820 --> 00:07:56.840
There does seem to be a difference.

00:07:56.840 --> 00:08:03.660
In terms of QT prolongation, there doesn't seem to be as much outside of ribuminib.

00:08:03.660 --> 00:08:07.480
And then just to kind of, this is the concluding slide, which I won't read you through.

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:12.060
But just highlighting the combinations are certainly encouraging in terms of responses,

00:08:12.060 --> 00:08:17.060
maybe decreased DS and other side effects, and hopefully may help overcome some of the

00:08:17.060 --> 00:08:18.620
monotherapy mechanisms of resistance.

00:08:18.620 --> 00:08:19.620
Great.

00:08:19.620 --> 00:08:20.620
Thank you.
